<br>
The problem is that we have to communicate when the need arises.  EVERY american citizen has the rights, AND the responsibilities of living in this country.  Suppose someone is a full american citizen but speaks no english.  Suppose they are sent to war, what good are they to the guy next to them if they can't communicate?  I am sure they would have someone in the group who can translate, maybe even have their whole group speak the same language... but how far does it go?<br>
<br>
I enjoy diversity.  I love Mexican food, love it twice as much in a place with authentic music and decorations, love it 10 times as much in the home of a mexican grand mother.  I even love the sound of the language.  I would love to be able to communicate though.  When I was in mexico I didn't expect them to speak my language, and I tried my hardest.  In my back yard its different.<br>
<br>
It is possible to hold on to your culture and still learn to speak english. <p><img src=http://www.mindspring.com/~cnjmorris/catcen.jpg>

